    "summary": "The Fall of Saigon on April 30, 1975, marked the end of the [[event:2674|Vietnam War]] and the reunification of Vietnam under communist rule. As North Vietnamese forces closed in on the South Vietnamese capital, a chaotic American evacuation — Operation Frequent Wind — airlifted over 7,000 American personnel and South Vietnamese nationals by helicopter from rooftops across the city. The iconic images of crowds desperate to board helicopters from the U.S. Embassy became one of the defining photographs of the Cold War era.\n\nThe fall came after the Paris Peace Accords of 1973 had nominally ended direct American military involvement while leaving North and South Vietnam locked in conflict. Congress had cut military aid to South Vietnam, and its armed forces, though large, proved unable to resist the final offensive. Saigon fell with little fighting as demoralized South Vietnamese military units dissolved. President Duong Van Minh surrendered unconditionally the morning of April 30.\n\nThe immediate aftermath saw roughly one million South Vietnamese detained in re-education camps, and hundreds of thousands of refugees — the boat people — fled by sea over the following years in desperate journeys with catastrophic death tolls. The unified Socialist Republic of Vietnam was proclaimed in 1976. For the United States, the fall represented a profound national trauma, reshaping military doctrine and foreign policy for decades. The term \"another Vietnam\" entered the political lexicon as a warning against open-ended military commitments.",
